Mesosoma.
Length of mesosoma 1.7 × as long as high (75: 45) (
Fig. 61
); propleuron crenulate; precoxal sulcus rather deep, crenulate (
Fig. 61
); mesopleuron sparsely finely punctate; subbalar space transversely rugose; metapleuron rugulose; mesoscutum finely rugo-punctate; notauli narrow and deep anteriorly, convergent posteriorly meeting deep median depression; scutellar sulcus 0.3 × as long as scutellum (5: 15) with five carinae; scutellum smooth; propodeum with strong raised median carina, which has strong lateral carinae transversely across its length (
Fig. 60
), rugulose laterally.

Fore wing
Pterostigma 5.0 × as long as wide (50: 10); vein M+CU1 straight; vein r arising far before middle of pterostigma; vein 1-SR+M strongly S-shaped (
Fig. 62
); vein cu-a postfurcal, perpendicular (
Fig. 62
); vein 2-CU1 10.25 × longer than 1-CU1; SR1: 3-SR: r = 50: 27: 10; vein 2-SR 3.0 × 2-SR+M (15: 5); 1-CU1: cu-a: 2-CU1: 3-CU1 = 4: 6: 41: 7; second submarginal cell large, basal length of second submarginal cell large, 3.2 × as long as its apical width (42: 13) (
Fig. 62
).

This new species is also similar with
C. chesmanae Quicke, 2012
, from Papua New Guinea , but can be distinguished from the latter by the following chracters: 1) Antenna with 47–49 flagellomeres ( 55 in
C. pukpuk
); 2) Fore wing vein 2-CU1 10.25 × longer than 1-CU1 (8.5 × longer than 1-CU 1 in
C. chesmanae
); 3) Hind wing vein M+CU 1.3 × as long as vein 1-M ( Fig. 63 ) (1.75 × in
C. chesmanae
); and 4) Mesosoma black or blackish brown (yellow in
C. chesmanae
).
